  <h1>What is Block of Assets?</h1>
  <div class="byline"><span class="av">SR</span><b>NumberIQ Glossary</b><span class="sep"></span><span>Last reviewed June 2026</span></div>
</header>
<div class="divide"></div>

<article class="prose read">
  <p class="answer-first lead"><b>A block of assets is a group of assets of the same class and depreciation rate, on which income-tax depreciation is computed collectively using the written-down value (WDV) method.</b></p>
  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <p>Additions are added to the block and sale proceeds are reduced from it; depreciation is charged on the block's WDV, so individual-asset gain or loss is generally not computed unless the block ceases.</p>
  <div class="callout law"><b>Reference.</b> Section 32, Income-tax Act.</div>
  <div class="faq"><h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <details><summary>What is a block of assets?</summary><p>A group of assets with the same class and depreciation rate, depreciated together on WDV under Section 32.</p></details>
    <details><summary>How is depreciation charged?</summary><p>On the written-down value of the whole block, after adjusting additions and sale proceeds.</p></details>
  </div>
  <div class="key-takeaways"><h2>Key takeaways</h2><ul><li>Assets are grouped into blocks by class and rate.</li><li>Depreciation is on the block's WDV.</li><li>Individual gain/loss arises only when a block ends.</li></ul></div>
